  "prompt": "Is the past tense of \"troubleshoot\" troubleshooted or troubleshot? Why?",
  "response": "The past tense of \"troubleshoot\" is \"troubleshot.\"\n\nThis follows the pattern of other irregular verbs like \"shoot\" (shot), \"foot\" (footed), where the past tense changes the vowel sound rather than simply adding \"-ed\". \n\n\"Troubleshot\" is the standard and most widely accepted form in both professional and informal contexts. While \"troubleshooted\" might occasionally be heard, it is not considered grammatically correct by most style guides and language experts.\n\nExample:\n- Present tense: I troubleshoot the computer system.\n- Past tense: I troubleshot the computer system yesterday.",
